Constructing Parallel Lines
Parallel lines are lines that lie in the same plane and do not intersect.
The lines in the first pair shown above intersect. They are clearly not parallel. The
lines in the second pair do not meet as drawn. However, if they were extended, they
would intersect. Therefore, they are not parallel. The lines in the third pair appear
to be parallel, but if you extend them far enough in both directions, can you be
sure they won't meet? There are many ways to be sure that the lines are parallel.
Investigation
Constructing Parallel Lines by Folding
How would you check whether two lines are parallel? One way is to draw a
transversal and compare corresponding angles. You can also use this idea to
construct a pair of parallel lines.
